e extended decentralized editing functions will be added later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How decentralized is the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nOur end goal is to run the BACKFEED magazine as a fully operational decentralized organization, governed and edited by a vibrant online community without any central point of control and powered by our protocol - which is designed exactly to this end. At the moment the only truly decentralized function is the homepage layout and curation, along with the reputation system for contributors and their compensation with Magazine-tokens. Wider editing functions, such as the screening and editing of articles pre-publishing, the placement of picture-art and the choice of headlines, are being currently developed and will be online later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How do I participate?\"]\r\n\r\nFirst thing to do is to register. After that, all that\'s left is your natural interaction with the magazine: Rate articles according to your taste and to the degree to which you find them relevant or insightful. Share items on social media, post comments, rate and respond to comments of others, and, if you\'re in the mood - submit your own article. Every such action is evaluated, and if it was helpful to the editorial process you will be rewarded with tokens and your reputation is likely to increase.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does the reputation system work?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is the measure of your alignment with the BACKFEED community. If your contributions are regarded as valuable by the community, your reputation increases, if they\'re seen as irrelevant, it decreases. - But that\'s not at all a reason to conform to the mainstream taste. On the contrary, if your taste deviates from the mainstream you might be the first one to spot an extraordinary contribution that was overseen by the crowd. Voting it up highlights it for the rest of the community, if it is then found to be useful, the algorithm compensates you to a much larger degree than those who just chase the herd. So be yourself and don\'t hesitate to express yourself.\r\n\r\nIf you want to learn more about the reputation system and the BACKFEED protocol in general, you can do so <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-backfeed-protocol-an-introduction-for-mere-mortals/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What\'s the difference between reputation and tokens?\"]\r\n\r\n<b>Reputation</b> represents your influence on the editorial process, it is calculated from the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are your share of the value we’ve created together, they signify how useful your input was to the editorial process.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are a transferable unit of value and function as a currency which can be bought and sold. <b>Reputation</b> is non-transferable and user specific.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are generated every time a contribution was identified as valuable. Their total amount is not fixed and increases as long as new value is added to the system. <b>Reputation</b>, in contrast, is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why is my reputation so low?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion]','FAQ','','inherit','closed','closed','','380-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 13:07:35','2016-02-15 13:07:35','',380,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/380-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(395,1,'2016-02-15 13:11:45','2016-02-15 13:11:45','[gravityform id=\"1\" title=\"false\" description=\"true\" ajax=\"true\"]','Submit Article','','publish','closed','closed','','submit-article','','','2016-04-14 11:50:24','2016-04-14 11:50:24','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?page_id=395',0,'page','',0),(396,8,'2016-02-15 13:10:54','2016-02-15 13:10:54',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','396','','','2016-04-24 16:22:39','2016-04-24 16:22:39','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=396',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(397,1,'2016-02-15 13:11:45','2016-02-15 13:11:45','','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 13:11:45','2016-02-15 13:11:45','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(399,1,'2016-02-15 13:18:52','2016-02-15 13:18:52','[contact-form-7 id=\"398\" title=\"Submit Article\"]','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 13:18:52','2016-02-15 13:18:52','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(402,8,'2016-02-15 13:32:13','2016-02-15 13:32:13','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We are a crowdsourced D-magazine! </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\r\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Everything you see here is  written by the BACKFEED community and edited by its collective intelligence.\r\nIf you want to learn more about how this works and why you should consider doing it, please visit the <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/article-submission/\">FAQ page</a></span>\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"398\" title=\"Submit Article\"]','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 13:32:13','2016-02-15 13:32:13','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(405,8,'2016-02-15 14:27:31','2016-02-15 14:27:31',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','405','','','2016-04-24 16:22:39','2016-04-24 16:22:39','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=405',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(406,8,'2016-02-15 14:34:25','2016-02-15 14:34:25','','tumblr_mx1olyYcw11sfie3io1_1280','','inherit','closed','closed','','tumblr_mx1olyycw11sfie3io1_1280','','','2016-02-15 14:34:25','2016-02-15 14:34:25','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/tumblr_mx1olyYcw11sfie3io1_1280.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(407,8,'2016-03-31 16:48:31','2016-03-31 16:48:31','[gravityform id=\"1\" title=\"false\" description=\"true\" ajax=\"true\"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Article submissions entail a XToken contribution fee. This is important in order to protect the system from malevolent flooding attacks. But no worries, this fee is easily outweighed by the bounty you\'ll receive the moment your article is rated as valuable by the community.</strong>','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-autosave-v1','','','2016-03-31 16:48:31','2016-03-31 16:48:31','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(408,8,'2016-02-15 16:18:16','2016-02-15 16:18:16','Backfeed is an open-source startup that develops a social operating system for decentralized organizations, allowing for massive open source collaboration without central administration. We provide the infrastructure for decentralized cooperation, allowing large groups to create collectively and  share the value they’ve created according to contribution. Our goal is to enable anyone, anywhere to effectively collaborate with their peers without having to erect fixed hierarchies and rigid structures. The core of our decentralized governance tools and value distribution algorithm is the BACKFEED protocol, about which you can learn <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a>.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Backfeed was founded in January 2015 by Matan Field (founder of </span><a href=\"http://lazooz.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">LaZooz.org</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">), Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard), Tal Serphos and Shahar Halutz. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the first 6 months of operation, we have finalized the development of our core technology (the Backfeed protocol); implemented a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) of the protocol, integrated in a Chrome extension over Slack; delivered the first prototype for a massive multi-player chess game as a proof of concept and established partnerships and collaboration opportunities with </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">strategic partners</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and like-minded individuals. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Backfeed is currently made up of an international team of about a dozen people (mainly from Europe and Israel) focused on building the foundational tools for decentralized collaborative organisations. Backfeed also enjoys a growing community of people interested in promoting the ideals of open and decentralized collaboration on a global scale.</span>\n\nFor more information about us, our technology and projects please visit our <a href=\"http://backfeed.cc\">website</a>','About us','','inherit','closed','closed','','112-autosave-v1','','','2016-02-15 16:18:16','2016-02-15 16:18:16','',112,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/112-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(409,8,'2016-02-15 16:18:19','2016-02-15 16:18:19','Backfeed is an open-source startup that develops a social operating system for decentralized organizations, allowing for massive open source collaboration without central administration. We provide the infrastructure for decentralized cooperation, allowing large groups to create collectively and  share the value they’ve created according to contribution. Our goal is to enable anyone, anywhere to effectively collaborate with their peers without having to erect fixed hierarchies and rigid structures. The core of our decentralized governance tools and value distribution algorithm is the BACKFEED protocol, about which you can learn <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Backfeed was founded in January 2015 by Matan Field (founder of </span><a href=\"http://lazooz.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">LaZooz.org</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">), Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard), Tal Serphos and Shahar Halutz. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the first 6 months of operation, we have finalized the development of our core technology (the Backfeed protocol); implemented a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) of the protocol, integrated in a Chrome extension over Slack; delivered the first prototype for a massive multi-player chess game as a proof of concept and established partnerships and collaboration opportunities with </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">strategic partners</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and like-minded individuals. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Backfeed is currently made up of an international team of about a dozen people (mainly from Europe and Israel) focused on building the foundational tools for decentralized collaborative organisations. Backfeed also enjoys a growing community of people interested in promoting the ideals of open and decentralized collaboration on a global scale.</span>\r\n\r\nFor more information about us, our technology and projects please visit our <a href=\"http://backfeed.cc\">website</a>','About us','','inherit','closed','closed','','112-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 16:18:19','2016-02-15 16:18:19','',112,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/112-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(410,8,'2016-02-18 09:41:43','2016-02-18 09:41:43','[agg_accordion multiselectable=\"false\"]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is Backfeed?\"]\nBackfeed is an open-source startup that develops a social operating system for decentralized organizations, allowing for massive open source collaboration without central administration. We provide the infrastructure for decentralized cooperation, allowing large groups to create collectively and  share the value they\'ve generated according to contribution. Our goal is to enable anyone, anywhere to effectively collaborate with their peers without having to erect fixed hierarchies and rigid structures. The core of our decentralized governance tools and value distribution algorithm is the BACKFEED protocol, about which you can learn <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a>.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is the BACKFEED Magazine?\"]\n\nDecentralization is one of the most important topics of our time with vast implications for every branch of social live; be it technology, economics, politics or culture. As an organization which recognizes the importance of this subject, and identifies it as one of the key elements for a prosperous future, we regard it as our responsibility to promote a wide ranging discussion about decentralization, the blockchain space and models for a collaborative economy; and you\'re invited to participate.\n\n<strong>We are a decentralized magazine</strong>, which essentially means that editing, writing and curation functions are delegated to the Backfeed community - which consists of our authors, readers and you, to the degree to which you’re interested in contributing. You can submit articles, rate the work of others and lead the discussion on topics brought forward here.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why should I be part of the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\n\nBecause it’s worth it!\n\nWe have a special algorithm that determines the value of each contribution - be it an article you’ve submitted, rating of such, an insightful comment or even the generation of traffic via shares and tweets. The value you’ve generated is transferred to you in form of Magazine-Tokens, which eventually might be worth real money. Read below how and when this happens.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What are Magazine tokens good for?\"]\n\nTokens signify the value you’ve contributed to the Backfeed magazine in form of articles, ratings, comments and shares. They represent the stake you hold in the collective editing process of our crowd-sourced magazine.  At the moment they’re mainly symbolic, but we have serious plans to monetize them.\n\nOne of the obvious ways would be selling ads exclusively in exchange for tokens, which would mean that advertisers would have to purchase tokens from you in order to publish ads here - granting  them real monetary value. <b>But since we don’t like ads</b>, we’re currently looking for other creative ways to monetize tokens. Charging tokens as an access fee for various forms of premium content is an option - which, again, would require readers to purchase them from you, turning them into a value baring cryptocurrency.\n\nHowever, we strongly recommend holding on to your tokens. In the meantime, subscribe so we can keep you up to date on this topic.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does decentralized editing work?\"]\n\nFrom the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours, our algorithm calculates a reputation score for you. This score determines how impactful you are in the editorial process. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\n\nThe reputation of all users is used by the algorithm to understand which contributions(submitted articles, comments, up/down votes) were valuable to the editorial process; tokens are then distributed to whomever lent a hand in a fruitful way.\n\nThis means that even your opinions on our articles, your up and down votes and your comments are worth (almost) genuine money (read above how) - after all, they’re what curates and edits this magazine.\n\nAt this point in time, the information gathered in the crowd-editing process is used to curate our front page and to decide which article will appear where. Further, more extended decentralized editing functions will be added later this year.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How decentralized is the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\n\nOur end goal is to run the BACKFEED magazine as a fully operational decentralized organization, governed and edited by a vibrant online community without any central point of control and powered by our protocol - which is designed exactly to this end. At the moment the only truly decentralized function is the homepage layout and curation, along with the reputation system for contributors and their compensation with Magazine-tokens. Wider editing functions, such as the screening and editing of articles pre-publishing, the placement of picture-art and the choice of headlines, are being currently developed and will be online later this year.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How do I participate?\"]\n\nFirst thing to do is to register. After that, all that\'s left is your natural interaction with the magazine: Rate articles according to your taste and to the degree to which you find them relevant or insightful. Share items on social media, post comments, rate and respond to comments of others, and, if you\'re in the mood - submit your own article. Every such action is evaluated, and if it was helpful to the editorial process you will be rewarded with tokens and your reputation is likely to increase.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does the reputation system work?\"]\n\nReputation is the measure of your alignment with the BACKFEED community. If your contributions are regarded as valuable by the community, your reputation increases, if they\'re seen as irrelevant, it decreases. - But that\'s not at all a reason to conform to the mainstream taste. On the contrary, if your taste deviates from the mainstream you might be the first one to spot an extraordinary contribution that was overseen by the crowd. Voting it up highlights it for the rest of the community, if it is then found to be useful, the algorithm compensates you to a much larger degree than those who just chase the herd. So be yourself and don\'t hesitate to express yourself.\n\nIf you want to learn more about the reputation system and the BACKFEED protocol in general, you can do so <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-backfeed-protocol-an-introduction-for-mere-mortals/\">here</a>.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What\'s the difference between reputation and tokens?\"]\n\n<b>Reputation</b> represents your influence on the editorial process, it is calculated from the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\n\n<b>Tokens</b> are your share of the value we’ve created together, they signify how useful your input was to the editorial process.\n\n<b>Tokens</b> are a transferable unit of value and function as a currency which can be bought and sold. <b>Reputation</b> is non-transferable and user specific.\n\n<b>Tokens</b> are generated every time a contribution was identified as valuable. Their total amount is not fixed and increases as long as new value is added to the system. <b>Reputation</b>, in contrast, is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why is my reputation so low?\"]\n\nReputation is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\n\n[/agg_accordion_item]\n\n[/agg_accordion]','FAQ','','inherit','closed','closed','','380-autosave-v1','','','2016-02-18 09:41:43','2016-02-18 09:41:43','',380,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/380-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(411,8,'2016-02-15 16:19:50','2016-02-15 16:19:50','[agg_accordion multiselectable=\"false\"]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is Backfeed?\"]\r\nBackfeed is an open-source startup that develops a social operating system for decentralized organizations, allowing for massive open source collaboration without central administration. We provide the infrastructure for decentralized cooperation, allowing large groups to create collectively and  share the value they\'ve generated according to contribution. Our goal is to enable anyone, anywhere to effectively collaborate with their peers without having to erect fixed hierarchies and rigid structures. The core of our decentralized governance tools and value distribution algorithm is the BACKFEED protocol, about which you can learn <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is the BACKFEED Magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nDecentralization is one of the most important topics of our time with vast implications for every branch of social live; be it technology, economics, politics or culture. As an organization which recognizes the importance of this subject, and identifies it as one of the key elements for a prosperous future, we regard it as our responsibility to promote a wide ranging discussion about decentralization, the blockchain space and models for a collaborative economy; and you\'re invited to participate.\r\n\r\n<strong>We are a decentralized magazine</strong>, which essentially means that editing, writing and curation functions are delegated to the Backfeed community - which consists of our authors, readers and you, to the degree to which you’re interested in contributing. You can submit articles, rate the work of others and lead the discussion on topics brought forward here.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why should I be part of the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nBecause it’s worth it!\r\n\r\nWe have a special algorithm that determines the value of each contribution - be it an article you’ve submitted, rating of such, an insightful comment or even the generation of traffic via shares and tweets. The value you’ve generated is transferred to you in form of Magazine-Tokens, which eventually might be worth real money. Read below how and when this happens.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What are Magazine tokens good for?\"]\r\n\r\nTokens signify the value you’ve contributed to the Backfeed magazine in form of articles, ratings, comments and shares. They represent the stake you hold in the collective editing process of our crowd-sourced magazine.  At the moment they’re mainly symbolic, but we have serious plans to monetize them.\r\n\r\nOne of the obvious ways would be selling ads exclusively in exchange for tokens, which would mean that advertisers would have to purchase tokens from you in order to publish ads here - granting  them real monetary value. <b>But since we don’t like ads</b>, we’re currently looking for other creative ways to monetize tokens. Charging tokens as an access fee for various forms of premium content is an option - which, again, would require readers to purchase them from you, turning them into a value baring cryptocurrency.\r\n\r\nHowever, we strongly recommend holding on to your tokens. In the meantime, subscribe so we can keep you up to date on this topic.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does decentralized editing work?\"]\r\n\r\nFrom the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours, our algorithm calculates a reputation score for you. This score determines how impactful you are in the editorial process. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\r\n\r\nThe reputation of all users is used by the algorithm to understand which contributions(submitted articles, comments, up/down votes) were valuable to the editorial process; tokens are then distributed to whomever lent a hand in a fruitful way.\r\n\r\nThis means that even your opinions on our articles, your up and down votes and your comments are worth <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Fls1C2LlvqFiIZl0rHF2n50ETNSSBcxiKCdtYPuvBtQ/edit#bookmark=id.u1xq69t46uyt\">(</a>almost) genuine money (read above how) - after all, they’re what curates and edits this magazine.\r\n\r\nAt this point in time, the information gathered in the crowd-editing process is used to curate our front page and to decide which article will appear where. Further, more extended decentralized editing functions will be added later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How decentralized is the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nOur end goal is to run the BACKFEED magazine as a fully operational decentralized organization, governed and edited by a vibrant online community without any central point of control and powered by our protocol - which is designed exactly to this end. At the moment the only truly decentralized function is the homepage layout and curation, along with the reputation system for contributors and their compensation with Magazine-tokens. Wider editing functions, such as the screening and editing of articles pre-publishing, the placement of picture-art and the choice of headlines, are being currently developed and will be online later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How do I participate?\"]\r\n\r\nFirst thing to do is to register. After that, all that\'s left is your natural interaction with the magazine: Rate articles according to your taste and to the degree to which you find them relevant or insightful. Share items on social media, post comments, rate and respond to comments of others, and, if you\'re in the mood - submit your own article. Every such action is evaluated, and if it was helpful to the editorial process you will be rewarded with tokens and your reputation is likely to increase.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does the reputation system work?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is the measure of your alignment with the BACKFEED community. If your contributions are regarded as valuable by the community, your reputation increases, if they\'re seen as irrelevant, it decreases. - But that\'s not at all a reason to conform to the mainstream taste. On the contrary, if your taste deviates from the mainstream you might be the first one to spot an extraordinary contribution that was overseen by the crowd. Voting it up highlights it for the rest of the community, if it is then found to be useful, the algorithm compensates you to a much larger degree than those who just chase the herd. So be yourself and don\'t hesitate to express yourself.\r\n\r\nIf you want to learn more about the reputation system and the BACKFEED protocol in general, you can do so <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-backfeed-protocol-an-introduction-for-mere-mortals/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What\'s the difference between reputation and tokens?\"]\r\n\r\n<b>Reputation</b> represents your influence on the editorial process, it is calculated from the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are your share of the value we’ve created together, they signify how useful your input was to the editorial process.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are a transferable unit of value and function as a currency which can be bought and sold. <b>Reputation</b> is non-transferable and user specific.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are generated every time a contribution was identified as valuable. Their total amount is not fixed and increases as long as new value is added to the system. <b>Reputation</b>, in contrast, is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why is my reputation so low?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion]','FAQ','','inherit','closed','closed','','380-revision-v1','','','2016-02-15 16:19:50','2016-02-15 16:19:50','',380,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/380-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(412,1,'2016-02-17 10:58:55','2016-02-17 10:58:55','In 1996, John Perry Barlow, american poet, writer for the Grateful Dead and cyber-libertarian activist had the admirable nerve to address the world economic forum in Davos, and share with the bewildered, Armani suited gentleman on scene the following “Declaration of the independence of cyberspace”, which went like this:\r\n<blockquote>Governments of the Industrial World, you weary giants of flesh and steel, I come from Cyberspace, the new home of Mind. On behalf of the future, I ask you of the past to leave us alone. You are not welcome among us. You have no sovereignty where we gather. [...] You have no moral right to rule us nor do you possess any methods of enforcement we have true reason to fear. [...]\r\nCyberspace consists of transactions, relationships, and thought itself, arrayed like a standing wave in the web of our communications. Ours is a world that is both everywhere and nowhere, but it is not where bodies live.\r\n[...] Your legal concepts of property, expression, identity, movement, and context do not apply to us. They are all based on matter, and there is no matter here.</blockquote>\r\n<img class=\" wp-image-300 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/1427078664521.jpg\" alt=\"1427078664521\" width=\"510\" height=\"287\" />\r\n\r\nThis manifesto of biblical wrath was published just a couple of years after the internet became publicly accessible, and it is to assume that the weary giants of flesh and steel, conferring only a few blocks from where it was first uploaded to become one of the first examples of the term “viral”, had only a very vague idea of what Barlow was talking about. The internet, back then, was to them this exotic thing some enthusiastic young rascals were claiming to be of utmost importance for some reason, just as the blockchain (or mainly bitcoin) is to our, contemporary fleshy steel giants.\r\n\r\nOptimistic times these were indeed. The belief that the State, ignorant of its helpless future, will soon be transcended, or even abolished in or by “cyberspace” was, and to a large degree - is, very common among people like John Perry Barlow. Obviously, they claim, “legal concepts of property, expression, identity and movement [..] are all based on matter, and there is no matter here.”\r\n\r\nBut are they really? Did the transcendent, immaterial nature of cyberspace protect it from the coarse fingers of the lords of mankind? 20 years have past since the declaration of the independence of cyberspace went viral; we have bitcoin millionaires walking among us that were literally born the day it was first uploaded, this eventually is the future Barlow wrote about so beautifully - could it be claimed that the past, as he prophesied, really left us alone?\r\n\r\nA lot went by in those 2 decades; we lived through 9/11 and its consequences, saw the entertainment industries kick and scream their path into the 21th century and heard Edward Snowden blow his unheeded whistles in front of everyone that dared to listen. It was a very turbulent time, here in the “New home of Mind”, and the weary giants of flesh and steel, from the private and public sector alike, seemed to have found their way to regulate the unregulatable in their favor.\r\n\r\nThere are several reasons for that. One of them is that the crude Law, cyber-libertarians so desperately want to escape from, is a far more complex phenomenon than they normally acknowledge. Its basis is not the material world alone, as stated in the above declaration, but the broader architecture in which human conduct is transacted. The code itself that governs the movement of information in cyberspace is such an architecture and it has proven itself to be far from immune to the manipulation and coercion that have their origins in the broader social, economic and political relations physically surrounding the internet in all its glory.\r\n\r\nBut here comes the blockchain! you might say - trustless, incorruptible, truly decentralized and without a single point of failure. Consisting of “transactions, relationships, and thought itself, arrayed like a standing wave in the web of our communications. Ours is a world that is both everywhere and nowhere, but it is not where bodies live.” Sounds familiar?\r\n\r\nWell, just as the Law and their Armani suited friends from Davos managed to put on their cyberspace suits, blow themselves to cyberspace to cyber-coopt the cyber-renegades from cyber-liberland, they’ll probably find their way into blockchainia as well, even if that means using the good old meatspace methods of brute force and armed men with funny hats and grim faces. As the example of 1996 has taught us - just because it is unregulatable, it doesn’t imply that it will stay like this forever.\r\n\r\n<img class=\" wp-image-302 alignright\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/blockchain-biz-billboard-2015-billboard-650.jpg\" alt=\"blockchain-biz-billboard-2015-billboard-650\" width=\"517\" height=\"342\" />\r\n\r\nJust as the internet as a whole, the blockchain community probably won\'t be able to escape the State, the Law and all their cronies, and neither should it try. The idea that all social relations could and should be reduced to trustless P2P contracts that enforce themselves is naive in its soft formulation and quite terrifying in its worst case. Even the blockchain economy will probably need the state to close the gaps and to serve as a trusted intermediary, and so does the public if it is interested in pursuing ideas of the common good that can’t necessarily be reduced to mutual arrangements between anonymous nodes, registering in a distributed ledger.\r\n\r\nInstead of aspiring a vertical liftoff into la-la land, we should ask ourselves how the obvious contradictions and conflicts inherent to the relationship between the State and the Blockchain could be mitigated, or even avoided.\r\n\r\nThe blockchain has an amazing potential to improve the State, fight corruption, level the playing field and reduce entry barriers for the poorest and most unprivileged among us. This potential can’t and won’t be utilized if we bamboozle ourselves with romantic ideas of an epic battle between the old and the new, between the weary giants of flesh and steel on one hand and the cyber rebellion on the other. Rather should the blockchain community use its skills and knowledge to provide examples of uncorrupted relations, better governance and fairer and more efficient markets and institutions.\r\n\r\nEstablished institutions already show much interest in decentralized technologies as a whole and the blockchain in particular, citizens all over the world, including in its most impoverished parts, are looking for opportunities to bypass corruption and develop trusted and more liable ways to manage their affairs. The blockchain should be introduced as a tool that assists them to do so and to improve their governments, and not necessarily as scheme to overthrow them.\r\n\r\nMaybe, this way the the ideals stated in our 1996 Declaration of the Independence could be achieved, just as it concludes - “We will create a civilization of the Mind in Cyberspace. May it be more humane and fair than the world your governments have made before.”\r\n\r\nThis post is inspired by Lawrence Lessigs presentation at the <a href=\"http://sydney.blockchainworkshops.org/index.html\">Sydney Blockchain Workshop</a>, NOV15, which is available <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/148665401\">here</a>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://vimeo.com/148665401[/embed]','Thinking through Law & Code - The Future of the State and The Blockchain','','inherit','closed','closed','','146-revision-v1','','','2016-02-17 10:58:55','2016-02-17 10:58:55','',146,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/146-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(413,12,'2016-02-17 14:37:00','2016-02-17 14:37:00','<blockquote>\r\nThe  author of this article lives in an income-sharing community in Virginia, Twin Oaks.  Twin Oaks is a communal group established in 1967 with 100 members.  Income is earned by businesses on the property. Everything is owned equally and no member gets any salary or wages.</blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There is a profound disconnect between what is taught about any trade, and the knowledge actually needed to perform that trade well. Medical students learn all the bones of the body, but are not taught how to listen carefully to patients. MBA students are taught personnel theories and the intersection of supply and demand, but not, say, how to deal with a mentally ill employee—or boss. This is because the central purpose of education is not mastery of useful skills, but through non-relevant rigorous requirements, screening people out. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What do business leaders say about this disconnect? It has become the bon-ton among corporate recruiters to claim no or little interest in student\'s grades. This might have some solid ground. In a famous </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">study</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> of air traffic controllers, a job requiring complex decision making, educational achievement made for worse air traffic controllers.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Not everyone ignores this. Twin</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Oaks is a complex society that runs several profitable businesses in addition to building buildings, fixing cars, and raising food; there is a great need for a wide array of skills. There are almost no barriers to taking on a task or job of almost any complexity. What Twin Oaks offers is on-the-job training—minus the training. A profound benefit of living at Twin Oaks is being able to be drawn to a job and to do it immediately, not after four or seven years of education, plus some additional handful of years working your way up through the ranks.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\" wp-image-419 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/photo-1452980904795-dc36a4d90da4-1024x492.jpg\" alt=\"photo-1452980904795-dc36a4d90da4\" width=\"512\" height=\"246\" />\r\nWhat the community has discovered is that training and credentials don\'t matter. Sure, a skilled plumber can fix a leaking pipe better than a philosophy student, but in two months of fixing leaking pipes, the philosophy student </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> a skilled plumber. Every member learns new skills, takes on new jobs—there are no hurdles in the way, other tha\r\nn willingness and competence. Sometimes people try a job and realize after a while that they don\'t like it, so they stop. Most members want variety in their work lives so no one chooses to do forty hours of the same job. Most members eventually sculpt a work life that is challenging, fulfilling, and rewarding.\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the mainstream, individuals claim to pursue education as a path to a more fulfilling life. What common threads of a fulfilling life should education be concerned with providing? Perhaps these: satisfying work, intellectual challenge, being of use, adequate pay. That is the implicit deal that higher education offers: sacrifice your childhood and young adulthood to us and in return your education will open the doors to a better, more bountiful, more challenging future. That is a promise that is increasingly broken.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Teenagers, intent on finding a career, must first gather all the credentials for that career before getting a chance to even see if they are suited to that work, but once they go through the time and expense to get the credentials, they are pretty well stuck with that career, whether they like it or not. Consequently, millions of people are in jobs that are other than they anticipated—lesser, worse—with no easy option for going back to square one and getting re-credentialed for another, more engaging career. After all, </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">this</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> job was worse than expected, the next could prove just as disappointing. One of the fastest growing segments of the student body at community colleges is people who already have a four-year degree and return to get a marketable skill. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">College serves another purpose—a purpose colleges don\'t mention in their course catalog— colleges habituate young people to accept a mismatch between form and content, official representations and reality. The passing of examinations, meeting of course deadlines, and disciplined study for the sake of mastering a body of knowledge demonstrates a willingness to conform to organizational discipline and displays the disposition needed to develop competence in a bureaucracy. Intellectuals pursue an academic career to become professionalized and this professionalization leads people not to higher intellectual rigor, but to stop thinking. The corporate world deals in abstractions, true, but trafficking in abstractions is not the same as thinking.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">White-collar professions have been routinized and degraded: standardized tests remove a teacher\'s discretion in the curriculum; strict sentencing guidelines prevent a judge from judging. Efforts of managers are not toward some tangible outcome. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The desire of hum<img class=\"wp-image-416 alignright\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/nails-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"nails\" width=\"460\" height=\"307\" />an nature is to effect change, to be recognized as a unique individual offering a special contribution to the world. Our failing struggle for personal agency is at the center of\r\nmodern life. Winnowed out through the funnel of education and specialization is a person\'s imagined goals—challenging work, suitable income, meaningful output, adequate leisure. We settle. Our lofty aspirations eventually dwindle to this: work is toilsome and necessarily serves someone else\'s interest. That\'s why we get paid. A key element in the mainstream economy\'s idealized self becomes not personal agency, but the capacity to surrender—enervation of judgment and erosion of the independent spirit.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To perpetuate this ignorance, contemporary culture separates knowing from doing. The way we come to know a hammer is not by staring at it, but grabbing hold of it and using it. The way things come to exist for us is not as free-floating objects out of context, but as equipment for action, within some actual worldly situation. If thinking is bound up with action, then the task of getting an adequate grasp on the world, intellectually, depends on us doing stuff in it. On all sides we see fewer occasions for the exercise of judgment, although human excellence calls forth the necessity of such judgment.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is a tragic loss to our society that manual competence is an ideal that finds little accommodation today. Some argue that it is irresponsible to educate the young for the trades, which are somehow identified with jobs of the past. We have a generation of students who can answer questions on tests, but who can\'t do anything. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The use of tools answers to some permanent requirement of our nature. Many people discover with surprise the greater sense of agency and competence that comes from doing manual work compared to \"knowledge work.\" More surprising is that people find manual work more engaging intellectually. The physical circumstances of jobs performed by carpenters, plumbers, and auto mechanics vary too much for them to be executed by idiots.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This labor makes one feel human, not like a cog in a machine. The trades draw those who live by their own powers, free not only of deadening abstraction, but also of the rising insecurities endemic to our current economic life. This work relieves us of the felt need to offer chattering interpretations of ourselves to vindicate our worth. We can simply point: the building stands, the car now runs, the garden is abundant. There is a cognitive richness of manual work; work that is useful proves to also be intellectually absorbing.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For many in mainstream society a good life is an amorphous goal. Living a meaningful life is seen as a foolish utopian dream. But it is not. Here at Twin Oaks our labor produces tangible outcomes that markedly improve our lives and the lives of those we live with. But more, our work brings us new skills, coherence to our lives, pleasure to our minds, and satisfaction to our souls.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Trades, Skill And Education - The Separation of Knowing From Doing','','publish','open','open','','trades-skill-education-separation-knowing','','','2016-03-10 08:54:37','2016-03-10 08:54:37','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=413',0,'post','',0),(414,8,'2016-02-17 14:08:34','2016-02-17 14:08:34','','oIpwxeeSPy1cnwYpqJ1w_Dufer Collateral test','','inherit','closed','closed','','oipwxeespy1cnwypqj1w_dufer-collateral-test','','','2016-02-17 14:08:34','2016-02-17 14:08:34','',413,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/oIpwxeeSPy1cnwYpqJ1w_Dufer-Collateral-test.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(415,8,'2016-02-17 14:08:43','2016-02-17 14:08:43','&nbsp;\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The  author of this article lives in an income-sharing community in Virginia, Twin Oaks.  Twin Oaks is a communal group established in 1967 with 100 members.  Income is earned by businesses on the property.  Everything is owned equally and no member gets any salary or wages.</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There is a profound disconnect between what is taught about any trade, and the knowledge actually needed to perform that trade well. Medical students learn all the bones of the body, but are not taught how to listen carefully to patients. MBA students are taught personnel theories and the intersection of supply and demand, but not, say, how to deal with a mentally ill employee—or boss. This is because the ce