iety and the individual in the interest of a ruling elite. Obviously, it is very difficult to argue with such a notion, since it is based on the fact that the privileged position such authorities occupy is abused on an almost regular basis, with disastrous consequences indeed.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">However, it would be a grave mistake to conclude that once such concentrations of power are dissolved, they’ll just leave a neutral void behind them which could be filled by a few premeditated algorithms that reduce all forms of social self-regulation to what is formulatable in smart contracts between consenting peers, technically eradicating the ability to have a communal discussion which leads to agreed upon decisions on a social level. Ignoring this could end us up in a system with truly despotic dynamics, resembling those of the pre-republican era, only this time with skynet like properties - which is, so we presume, pitchfork and guillotine resilient.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Every system needs built-in mechanisms that allow for the resolvement of conflicts, improvement and growth. Every now and then these mechanisms need to be more complex and intelligent than those provided by local P2P interactions - which are great to foster and boost market dynamics, but are algorithmically speaking, fairly unintelligent and inappropriate when the network faces systemic crises. The Bitcoin network, despite the remarkable invention it is, demonstrates how crucial this is. As the system needs to be upgraded and adjusted to a new reality, it in itself doesn’t provide any decentralized means of doing so. All the discussions about what should be done next are held offline in meatspace and are controlled by a small elite group which makes the real-existing mainstream financial system look like a beacon of democracy.    </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still, many envision a future in which Bitcoin, or something like it, would eventually serve as the (or a) global reserve currency - doing away once and for all with central banks, capital controls and taxes. This is a vision that might sound appealing to many, but would, at the current state of affairs, actually be a disaster with apocalyptic consequences.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The deflationary character of Bitcoin (and most of its current alternatives), would lead world markets to a squeaking hold. Investment would probably stop immediately, since holding on to your currency would be a much safer way of making a profit then investing it in shaky businesses or lending it. As a result, interest rates would skyrocket, social mobility would disappear almost completely, unemployment would be the general norm and every form of inequality would be magnified a dozen times over - And that is just in regard of one aspect of the currency. The inability to actively and consciously intervene in the magnitude of the money supply could actually mean the end of capitalism as we know it; and no, not in a good way. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In addition to that, catastrophic </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_failure\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">market failures</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, occurrences of </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underconsumption\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">underconsumption</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> dynamics, </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_swan_theory\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">black swan</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> events and all their like, are only the beginning of a long list of systematic examples that would require those concerned to reach consensus regarding the appropriate systematic solutions. The Bitcoin elite is either ideologically blind to these issues or would like you to believe that they just need more time and that they’ll have it all sorted out in the next bitcoin core update, but it seems that there are many reasons to beg to differ.  </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">So how then should we cope with the reality of living in a somewhat chaotic and unpredictable universe? Traditionally we’ve delegated this function to elected officials and their appointed “experts” (with or without quotation marks, depending on your taste), which performed mediocre in most cases, disastrous in some, and very seldom excelled. As such, they undoubtedly deserve to be automatized out of history, the only question remaining is by what, and what role human individuals and society as whole will play in such a scenario.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If, as stated above, technology is the enhancement of human ability through tools, then the process of decentralization via blockchains, p2p networks, smart contracts and who knows what might come next, should ameliorate our ability to solve social conflicts, reach consensus and address systemic problems, rather than trying to abolish it altogether. In that respect, decentralisation should be the leveling up of democracy, social discourse and communal problem solving, and not its grave, as some might suggest or even hope.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This is not, god forbid, an apologetic for centralized, and mostly corrupt, institutions like central banks and their cigar smoking affiliates with gray suits and a severe lack of humor. It is a reminder of the fact, that if we’re interested in taking the project of decentralization seriously, we should come up with a decentralized substitute for those centralized institutions we’re rightfully so fond of bashing.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But how are we going to do that? Unfortunately, humanity has never done that before so there’s no user manual or best practices to draw from. All we can do is learn from our mistakes, stay ideological unbiased, and choose the right attitude - An attitude that seeks to empower humans, rather than one that tries to get rid of them, and which accounts for the fact that in a world of decentralized markets, networks and crowdsourced AI\'s, the need for decentralized government structures will be even more acute than it is now or ever was before.    </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span>','The Fallacy Of Getting Rid Of Humans','','inherit','closed','closed','','477-revision-v1','','','2016-03-10 16:39:54','2016-03-10 16:39:54','',477,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/477-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(482,8,'2016-03-10 16:52:33','2016-03-10 16:52:33','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The decentralization discourse is maybe one of the most diverse topics in contemporary culture. It has nodes, so to speak, in the realms of economics, politics, communication and even </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralised_system#Naturally_occurring_decentralised_systems\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">biology</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Mainly though, living in a computational age of networks of networks, it has become foremost a technological topic. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Technology” in that respect means Technology with a capital T- in its broadest sense possible: The enhancement of human ability through tools carved out of the interaction between imagination and matter.  </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In this regard one could say that what the wheel and the internal combustion engine did to human muscle power, and the computer to the central nervous system - distributed ledgers, smart contracts and single sources of truth are attempting to apply to human relations and modes of organization. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\" wp-image-480 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/15036695694_b21cd95b53_o-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"15036695694_b21cd95b53_o\" width=\"486\" height=\"274\" />This endeavor of automatizing social institutions could indeed be called The Great Project of our age. Our generation didn’t make that up of course. In some sense it began when constitutional republics started to replace despots of all kinds, and shifted decision making from an authority based system to one relying on a set of syntax based processes, agreed upon by society as a whole - which we call today The Rule of Law. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Since humanity’s discovered what a smart-contract is, however, it became obvious, if not inevitable to imagine a fully automated and self executing Rule of Law. One hardcoded on top of the Blockchain, streamlined, incorruptible  and subjected only to an internal logic which is freed from subjective opinions and human failure, and in some sense freed from society itself.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This state of affairs, if it will eventually become a reality, would be the ultimate automation of human society and transform our social institutions into giant crowdsourced AI’s. Like with any wave of automation, this holds the potential for an upsurge in productivity, accompanied with probable social tensions, but eventually, so is generally hoped, the promise of the redistribution of social influence and wealth. Afterall, that’s why we’re all here, and that’s what makes said project so great.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">However, one should not fall for the fallacy of believing that it is possible, or even desirable, to eliminate human involvement from active decision making on a social level. Actually, if anything, it should work the other way around. The process of decentralization, and the elimination of intermediates and trusted third parties, should foster a greater sense of agency and involvement in social discourse for both - individuals and groups alike. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Obvious as this might sound, it isn’t clear at all how such a process should unfold and what would and should remain of social institutions as we know them today, if and when our Great Project should reach its ultimate goal (if there is such a thing).</span>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_340\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"339\"]<a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-bitcoin-debacle-making-the-case-for-decentralized-governance/ \"><img class=\"wp-image-340\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/hindenburg-397013-1024x780.jpg\" alt=\"hindenburg-397013\" width=\"339\" height=\"258\" /></a> Read about the Bitcoin Debacle[/caption]\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-bitcoin-debacle-making-the-case-for-decentralized-governance/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Bitcoin project highlights this </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">controversy more than anything. Its ability to bypass, and even subvert, regulators and lawmakers led many to believe that the function they execute is redundant altogether, since such centers of control presumably serve no end rather than that of the submission and perversion of society and the individual in the interest of a ruling elite. Obviously, it is very difficult to argue with such a notion, since it is based on the fact that the privileged position such authorities occupy is abused on an almost regular basis, with disastrous consequences indeed.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">However, it would be a grave mistake to conclude that once such concentrations of power are dissolved, they’ll just leave a neutral void behind them which could be filled by a few premeditated algorithms that reduce all forms of social self-regulation to what is formulatable in smart contracts between consenting peers, technically eradicating the ability to have a communal discussion which leads to agreed upon decisions on a social level. Ignoring this could end us up in a system with truly despotic dynamics, resembling those of the pre-republican era, only this time with skynet like properties - which is, so we presume, pitchfork and guillotine resilient.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Every system needs built-in mechanisms that allow for the resolvement of conflicts, improvement and growth. Every now and then these mechanisms need to be more complex and intelligent than those provided by local P2P interactions - which are great to foster and boost market dynamics, but are algorithmically speaking, fairly unintelligent and inappropriate when the network faces systemic crises. The Bitcoin network, despite the remarkable invention it is, demonstrates how crucial this is. As the system needs to be upgraded and adjusted to a new reality, it in itself doesn’t provide any decentralized means of doing so. All the discussions about what should be done next are held offline in meatspace and are controlled by a small elite group which makes the real-existing mainstream financial system look like a beacon of democracy.    </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still, many envision a future in which Bitcoin, or something like it, would eventually serve as the (or a) global reserve currency - doing away once and for all with central banks, capital controls and taxes. This is a vision that might sound appealing to many, but would, at the current state of affairs, actually be a disaster with apocalyptic consequences.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The deflationary character of Bitcoin (and most of its current alternatives), would lead world markets to a squeaking hold. Investment would probably stop immediately, since holding on to your currency would be a much safer way of making a profit then investing it in shaky businesses or lending it. As a result, interest rates would skyrocket, social mobility would disappear almost completely, unemployment would be the general norm and every form of inequality would be magnified a dozen times over - And that is just in regard of one aspect of the currency. The inability to actively and consciously intervene in the magnitude of the money supply could actually mean the end of capitalism as we know it; and no, not in a good way. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In addition to that, catastrophic </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_failure\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">market failures</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, occurrences of </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underconsumption\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">underconsumption</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> dynamics, </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_swan_theory\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">black swan</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> events and all their like, are only the beginning of a long list of systematic examples that would require those concerned to reach consensus regarding the appropriate systematic solutions. The Bitcoin elite is either ideologically blind to these issues or would like you to believe that they just need more time and that they’ll have it all sorted out in the next bitcoin core update, but it seems that there are many reasons to beg to differ.  </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">So how then should we cope with the reality of living in a somewhat chaotic and unpredictable universe? Traditionally we’ve delegated this function to elected officials and their appointed “experts” (with or without quotation marks, depending on your taste), which performed mediocre in most cases, disastrous in some, and very seldom excelled. As such, they undoubtedly deserve to be automatized out of history, the only question remaining is by what, and what role human individuals and society as whole will play in such a scenario.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If, as stated above, technology is the enhancement of human ability through tools, then the process of decentralization via blockchains, p2p networks, smart contracts and who knows what might come next, should ameliorate our ability to solve social conflicts, reach consensus and address systemic problems, rather than trying to abolish it altogether. In that respect, decentralisation should be the leveling up of democracy, social discourse and communal problem solving, and not its grave, as some might suggest or even hope.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This is not, god forbid, an apologetic for centralized, and mostly corrupt, institutions like central banks and their cigar smoking affiliates with gray suits and a severe lack of humor. It is a reminder of the fact, that if we’re interested in taking the project of decentralization seriously, we should come up with a decentralized substitute for those centralized institutions we’re rightfully so fond of bashing.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But how are we going to do that? Unfortunately, humanity has never done that before so there’s no user manual or best practices to draw from. All we can do is learn from our mistakes, stay ideological unbiased, and choose the right attitude - An attitude that seeks to empower humans, rather than one that tries to get rid of them, and which accounts for the fact that in a world of decentralized markets, networks and crowdsourced AI\'s, the need for decentralized government structures will be even more acute than it is now or ever was before.    </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span>','The Fallacy Of Getting Rid Of Humans','','inherit','closed','closed','','477-revision-v1','','','2016-03-10 16:52:33','2016-03-10 16:52:33','',477,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/477-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(483,8,'2016-03-10 16:58:18','2016-03-10 16:58:18','','2906353344_37c1e8fbd8_o','','inherit','open','closed','','2906353344_37c1e8fbd8_o','','','2016-03-10 16:58:18','2016-03-10 16:58:18','',477,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/