cating the ability to have a communal discussion which leads to agreed upon decisions on a social level. Ignoring this could end us up in a system with truly despotic dynamics, resembling those of the pre-republican era, only this time with skynet like properties - which is, so we presume, pitchfork and guillotine resilient.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Every system needs built-in mechanisms that allow for the resolvement of conflicts, its improvement and growth. Every now and then these mechanisms need to be more complex and intelligent than those provided by local P2P interactions - which are great to foster and boost market dynamics, but are algorithmically speaking, fairly unintelligent and inappropriate when the network faces systemic crises. The Bitcoin network, despite the remarkable invention it is, demonstrates how crucial this is. As the system needs to be upgraded and adjusted to a new reality, it in itself doesn’t provide any decentralized means of doing so. All the discussions about what should be done next are held offline in meatspace and are controlled by a small elite group which makes the real-existing mainstream financial system look like a beacon of democracy.    </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still, many envision a future in which Bitcoin, or something like it, would eventually serve as the (or a) global reserve currency - doing away once and for all with central banks, capital controls and taxes. This is a vision that might sound appealing to many, but would, at the current state of affairs, actually be a disaster with apocalyptic consequences.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The deflationary character of Bitcoin (and most of its current alternatives), would lead world markets to a squeaking hold. Investment would probably stop immediately, since holding on to your currency would be a much safer way of making a profit then investing it in shaky businesses or lending it. As a result, interest 