an Field. December 2015, Tel-Aviv.  </p>','Enabling spontaneous, Large-Scale Collaboration','','inherit','closed','closed','','192-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:35:48','2016-03-21 08:35:48','',192,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/192-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(557,1,'2016-03-21 08:38:50','2016-03-21 08:38:50','<p><span style=\"line-height: 28.8px;\">[embed]</span>https://youtu.be/SsCxgez1XBo<span style=\"line-height: 28.8px;\">[/embed]</span></p><p>The idea that in the future tokens will play a crucial role in networks and organizations to incentivize decentralized collaboration and reward contribution is not new. It\'s the original decentralized autonomous organization idea that has informed many projects that have been on the podcast (Swarm, Ethereum, Factom, Storj, etc). For Matan, the vision originally led to found decentralized ride-sharing application LaZooz. One year ago, he left LaZooz to found Backfeed, which is building the tools that so far have been missing to make mass collaboration without a central party possible. Topics covered included: - How he became interested in blockchains and started the ridesharing application LaZooz - Backfeed\'s vision for a social operating system for decentralized organizations - The role of reputation, proof-of-value and tokens in Backfeed - The applications Backfeed is currently building - The business of model of Backfeed</p>','Matan Field on Epicenter Bitcoin: Backfeed And The Social Operating System For Decentralized Organizations','','inherit','closed','closed','','348-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:38:50','2016-03-21 08:38:50','',348,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(558,1,'2016-03-21 08:39:06','2016-03-21 08:39:06','<p>[embed]https://youtu.be/SsCxgez1XBo[/embed]</p><p>The idea that in the future tokens will play a crucial role in networks and organizations to incentivize decentralized collaboration and reward contribution is not new. It\'s the original decentralized autonomous organization idea that has informed many projects that have been on the podcast (Swarm, Ethereum, Factom, Storj, etc). For Matan, the vision originally led to found decentralized ride-sharing application LaZooz. One year ago, he left LaZooz to found Backfeed, which is building the tools that so far have been missing to make mass collaboration without a central party possible. Topics covered included: - How he became interested in blockchains and started the ridesharing application LaZooz - Backfeed\'s vision for a social operating system for decentralized organizations - The role of reputation, proof-of-value and tokens in Backfeed - The applications Backfeed is currently building - The business of model of Backfeed</p>','Matan Field on Epicenter Bitcoin: Backfeed And The Social Operating System For Decentralized Organizations','','inherit','closed','closed','','348-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:39:06','2016-03-21 08:39:06','',348,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(559,1,'2016-03-21 08:40:23','2016-03-21 08:40:23','<p>https://soundcloud.com/bitcoincombr/podcast-bitcoincombr-1-primavera-de-filippi-backfeed</p><p>Primavera talks about how the idea of \"Proof of Value\" came into being, and how it relates to the future of blockchain based, decentralized organizations. The original interview can be found <a href=\"https://bitcoin.com.br/podcast-1-primavera-de-filippi-backfeed-transcript/\">here</a></p>','Primavera De Filippi on Bitcoin.com.br - Backfeed and proof of value','','inherit','closed','closed','','353-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:40:23','2016-03-21 08:40:23','',353,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/353-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(560,1,'2016-03-21 08:40:50','2016-03-21 08:40:50','<p>[embed]https://soundcloud.com/bitcoincombr/podcast-bitcoincombr-1-primavera-de-filippi-backfeed[/embed]</p><p>Primavera talks about how the idea of \"Proof of Value\" came into being, and how it relates to the future of blockchain based, decentralized organizations. The original interview can be found <a href=\"https://bitcoin.com.br/podcast-1-primavera-de-filippi-backfeed-transcript/\">here</a></p>','Primavera De Filippi on Bitcoin.com.br - Backfeed and proof of value','','inherit','closed','closed','','353-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:40:50','2016-03-21 08:40:50','',353,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/353-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(561,1,'2016-03-21 08:41:48','2016-03-21 08:41:48','<p>[embed]https://youtu.be/LEJ5qvcvnp4[/embed]</p><p>A presentation by Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard) at <span id=\"eow-title\" class=\"watch-title \" dir=\"ltr\" title=\"Distributed Collobrative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015\">COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015</span>, followed by a panel hosting Simon de la Rouvière (Consensys), Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard). Moderated by Constance Choi (Seven Advisory)</p>','Distributed Collaborative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015','','inherit','closed','closed','','434-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:41:48','2016-03-21 08:41:48','',434,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/434-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(562,1,'2016-03-21 08:42:41','2016-03-21 08:42:41','<p>[embed]https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PN-JLKBiVGY[/embed]</p><p>Primavera De Filippi, researcher at CNRS and faculty associate at the Berkman Center, Harvard Law School, is investigating emergent decentralized technologies to design new governance models.</p>','Primavera De Filippi - Blockchain Technology and the Future of Work','','inherit','closed','closed','','460-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 08:42:41','2016-03-21 08:42:41','',460,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/460-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(566,1,'2016-03-21 15:08:56','2016-03-21 15:08:56','[gravityform id=\"2\" title=\"false\" description=\"true\" ajax=\"true\"]','Contact Us','','inherit','closed','closed','','511-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 15:08:56','2016-03-21 15:08:56','',511,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/511-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(568,1,'2016-03-21 15:10:55','2016-03-21 15:10:55','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We are a crowdsourced D-magazine! </span>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Everything you see here is  written by the BACKFEED community and edited by its collective intelligence.\r\nIf you want to learn more about how this works and why you should consider doing it, please visit the <a href=\"/faq/\">FAQ page</a></span>\r\n\r\n[gravityform id=\"1\" title=\"false\" description=\"true\" ajax=\"true\"]','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 15:10:55','2016-03-21 15:10:55','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(569,1,'2016-04-12 16:12:21','2016-04-12 16:12:21','<h4>All newly submitted articles appear here in chronological order. Your input is what promotes them to the Front Page or hides them from the general public. Hanging out here can be very profitable.</h4>\r\n&nbsp;','Raw Space','','publish','closed','closed','','raw-space','','','2016-04-25 13:30:25','2016-04-25 13:30:25','',0,'http://dmagbeta.backfeed.cc/?page_id=624',0,'page','',0),(570,1,'2016-03-21 15:12:08','2016-03-21 15:12:08','[gravityform id=\"1\" title=\"false\" description=\"true\" ajax=\"true\"]','Submit Article','','inherit','closed','closed','','395-revision-v1','','','2016-03-21 15:12:08','2016-03-21 15:12:08','',395,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/395-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(571,26,'2016-03-22 14:20:37','2016-03-22 14:20:37','<em><strong>As opposed to other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars, which were predicted and anticipated long before, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible  numbers, made possible by rearranging information and technologies we had for years. This, says Gabriel Aleixo, a researcher and project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>, is where the real disruptive potential lies. </strong></em>\r\n\r\nWhenever some kind of revolution starts, there are always the ones who acknowledge its transformations at the very beginning and those who keep believing it is a fad or just a newer instance of something we already had for so long. Right now, there is no better example of that than the emergence of blockchain as a multi-purpose technology, and the myriad of projects that followed its successful creation/deployment in Bitcoin. In the case of the cryptocurrency, even with some significant coverage from the mainstream press many, dismiss it as a mere payment processing tool, no better than the ones offered by hundreds of small startups all over the world. Honestly, this is not necessarily wrong in any way, as some of the enthusiasts like me might think.\r\n\r\nOf course, we will have companies and institutions deliberately attempting to fight it, as these technologies could represent such a progress for society in general that many of their professionals - especially in the intermediation businesses - could not be needed anymore in a few years. But my point is that blockchain technologies have the power to directly lead to a paradigm shift so profound that many could not even relate to this process, inasmuch as that they did not consider something like it before. This is why even among the optimistic crowd some can not go further than limited analogies to existing technologies they think to be utterly innovative.\r\n\r\nIn this regard, it is important to keep in mind, that if we deconstruct Blockchain technology, we really won\'t find entirely new concepts. Public-key cryptography  and distributed networks, for example, have been out there for years. The novelty in blockchain technology, however, consists in its unique capability of generating and communicating consensus about a common database which is maintained and updated through a decentralized network. This in it self was built by rearranging how technologies (we did know very well before) interact in a single technical protocol, so that they could finally solve the problem of random peers agreeing with each other without relying on centralized trust. As Ludwig Wittgenstein wrote in his Philosophical Investigations:\r\n<blockquote>The problems are solved, not by giving new information, but by arranging what we have known since long.\r\nLudwig Wittgenstein (1953).</blockquote>\r\nThe Blockchain concept arose as part of a protocol to secure the creation and the transference of cryptographic tokens, intended to be used as electronic cash, something many brilliant minds in Computer Science considered to be impossible for decades. Differently from other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars which were predicted long before and affected our perspectives of the future, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible numbers, made possible by rearranging information we had for years. Of course there is a huge infrastructure behind it, which costs a lot in terms of energy and equipment, but in the bottom line the technology itself has more to do with the knowledge it embodies and freely spreads as open source code.\r\n\r\nIn this sense, F. A. Hayek points out very clearly in his seminal work The Constitution of Liberty:\r\n<blockquote>The growth of knowledge is of such special importance because, while the material resources will always remain scarce and will have to be reserved for limited purposes, the uses of new knowledge (where we do not make them artificially scarce by patents of monopoly) are unrestricted. Knowledge, once achieved, becomes gratuitously available for the benefit of all. It is through this free gift of the knowledge acquired by the experiments of some members of society that general progress is made possible, that the achievements of those who have gone before facilitate the advance of those who follow.\r\nF.A. Hayek (1960).</blockquote>\r\nThis is why we have this very unique situation. Even if new blockchain-based protocols like Bitcoin or Backfeed lack this materiality (at least for now), the way they can be freely adapted, replicated or deployed is very peculiar, being essentially knowledge gratuitously available for experimentation. We still have to cross the learning curve of programming and even using some of these tools, but at least it seems possible to mantain large and secure distributed networks as public resources, especially when combined with the market incentives built in Bitcoin or Ethereum. How to grow and sustain a decentralized governance is an issue, but as Bill Gates noted blockchain-based technologies are exciting because they are “cheap”. They provide opportunities for real innovation in the foreseeable future in areas dominated by a few players today.\r\n\r\nTake financial services and entrepreneurship as an example. Naturally, things are not going to entirely change in a year or two. But the fact is that, technically speaking, we now have the tools to transform an “exclusive game” in a more inclusive one. These changes are working in a way to include more people through decentralization. In the past, if you had 1000 dollars in your bank account you were very limited in how to protect your savings from inflation or in how to invest them in a new business. If you had 100000 dollars, things definitely got better in terms of accessing better financial tools or being part of an interesting investment fund, but you were still very limited in your possibilities compared to someone who held 10 million dollars. From now on, with blockchain, we can significantly decentralize such services and made them equally available for a much wider range of people. Small savings from people all over the world put together can easily be part of funding a sucessful startup, rather than a few institutional investors, as crowdfunding and equity distribution start to become a thing in blockchain-based platforms.  And no matter if we are talking about 1 dollar or 1 million dollars, hedging tools are also another trend emerging in the cryptoassets and smart contracts arena to decentralize and promote inclusive transformation.\r\n<blockquote>Smart companies will get out of the way and help the inevitable to happen sooner.\r\n\r\nThe Cluetrain Manifesto (1999)</blockquote>\r\nFor sure, these advances alone are not going to address everything that needs to be fixed in the world. If we look closer, they are actually just a small step, but a very exciting one, for a specific reason. It is not just a matter of providing new tools and working to making them as user-friendly as possible, it is a matter of proposing technologies that are able to transform us socially, not only technically. I am not excited for the 1000-dollar guy simply because he is going to save 100 or 200 bucks in purchasing power using a blockchain-based hedging tool that otherwise would not be accessible to him, nor I am too excited for his possibility of becoming the owner of a small share of the next big thing. These things are going to be important, for him and for us. But the major point here is how they can significantly change the mind and the behavior of many people, currently excluded from economies in general, as soon as they realize that they are actually transforming themselves in entrepreneurs and investors by saving a little money. Concepts like “entrepreneur”, “business” and “investor” can be redefined sooner than most of us expect if this process goes on. With blockchain, we started a journey of as many heroes as we want, even if many of them did not realize they will be part of it yet.\r\n\r\nGabriel Aleixo is a Researcher and Project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>','Blockchain - a journey of infinite heroes','','draft','open','open','','blockchain-journey-infinite-heroes','','','2016-04-04 11:41:20','2016-04-04 11:41:20','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=571',0,'post','',0),(572,8,'2016-03-22 13:37:53','2016-03-22 13:37:53','','gabriel','','inherit','open','closed','','gabriel','','','2016-03-22 13:37:53','2016-03-22 13:37:53','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/gabriel.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(573,8,'2016-03-22 13:50:44','2016-03-22 13:50:44','<em><strong>As opposed to other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars, which were predicted and anticipated long before, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible  numbers, made possible by rearranging information and technologies we had for years. This, says Gabriel Aleixo, a researcher and project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>, is where the real disruptive potential lies. </strong></em>\r\n\r\nWhenever some kind of revolution starts, there are always the ones who acknowledge its transformations at the very beginning and those who keep believing it is a fad or just a newer instance of something we already had for so long. Right now, there is no better example of that than the emergence of blockchain as a multi-purpose technology, and the myriad of projects that followed its successful creation/deployment in Bitcoin. In the case of the cryptocurrency, even with some significant coverage from the mainstream press many dismiss it as a mere payment processing tool, no better than the ones offered by hundreds of small startups all over the world. Honestly, this is not necessarily wrong in any way, as some of the enthusiasts like me might think.\r\n\r\nOf course, we will have companies and institutions deliberately attempting to fight it, as these technologies could represent such a progress for society in general that many of their professionals - especially in the intermediation businesses - could not be needed anymore in a few years. But my point is that blockchain technologies have the power to directly lead to a paradigm shift so profound that many could not even relate a minimum to this process, considering that they did not watch or consider something like it before. This is why even among the optimistic crowd some can not go further than limited analogies with technologies they think that are utterly innovative, like seeing blockchain as a radically transformative tool simply because it could be one of the responsibles for the Uberization of new services.\r\n\r\nIt is also important to note that if we split blockchain technology elements, it is not made out of entirely new concepts. Public-key cryptography  and distributed networks had been out there for years, for example. The novelty in blockchain technology consists in its unique capability of generating and communicating consensus about a common database which is mantained and updated through a decentralized network. And, once more, it was built by rearranging how technologies (we did know very well before) interact in a single technical protocol, so that they could finally solve the problem of random peers agreeing with each other without relying on centralized trust. As Ludwig Wittgenstein wrote in his Philosophical Investigations:\r\n<blockquote>The problems are solved, not by giving new information, but by arranging what we have known since long.\r\nLudwig Wittgenstein (1953).</blockquote>\r\nThis is yet another fact to take in account for the difficulty the audience in general has to understand not exactly the technology itself but its major implications. Blockchain arose as part of a protocol to secure the creation and the transference of cryptographic tokens, intended to be used as electronic cash, something many brilliant minds in Computer Science considered to be impossible for decades. Differently from other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars which were predicted long before and affect our perspectives in the moment we see them and realize they are finally happening, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and intangible (for most) numbers, made possible by rearranging information we had for years. Of course there is a huge infrastructure behind it, which costs a lot in terms of energy and equipment, but in the bottom line the technology itself has more to do with the knowledge it embodies and freely spreads as open source code.\r\n\r\nIn this sense, F. A. Hayek points out very clearly in his seminal work The Constitution of Liberty:\r\n<blockquote>The growth of knowledge is of such special importance because, while the material resources will always remain scarce and will have to be reserved for limited purposes, the uses of new knowledge (where we do not make them artificially scarce by patents of monopoly) are unrestricted. Knowledge, once achieved, becomes gratuitously available for the benefit of all. It is through this free gift of the knowledge acquired by the experiments of some members of society that general progress is made possible, that the achievements of those who have gone before facilitate the advance of those who follow.\r\nF.A. Hayek (1960).</blockquote>\r\nThis is why we have this very unique situation. Even if new blockchain-based protocols like Bitcoin or Backfeed lack this materiality (at least for now), the way they can be freely adapted, replicated or deployed is very peculiar, being essentially knowledge gratuitously available for experimentation these days. We still have to cross the learning curve of programming and even using some of these tools, but at least it seems possible to mantain large and secure distributed networks as public resources, especially when combined with the market incentives built in Bitcoin or Ethereum. How to grow and sustain a decentralized governance is an issue, but as Bill Gates noted blockchain-based technologies are exciting because they are “cheap”. They provide opportunities for real innovation in the foreseeable future in areas dominated by a few players today.\r\n\r\nTake financial services and entrepreneurship as an example. Naturally, things are not going to entirely change in a year or two. But the fact is that, technically speaking, we now have the tools to transform an “exclusive game” in a more inclusive one. These changes are working in a way to include more people through decentralization. In the last years, if you had 1000 dollars in your bank account you were totally limited on how to protect your savings from inflation or how to invest it in a new business. If you had 100000 dollars, things definitely got better in terms of accessing better financial tools or being part of an interesting investment fund, but you were still very limited in your possibilities compared to someone who held 10 million dollars. From now on with blockchain, we can significantly decentralize such services and made them equally available for a much wider range of people. Small savings from people all over the world put together can easily be part of funding a sucessful startup, rather than a few institutional investors, as crowdfunding and equity distribution start to become a thing in blockchain-based platforms.  And no matter if we are talking about 1 dollar or 1 million dollars, hedging tools are also another trend emerging in the cryptoassets and smart contracts arena to decentralize and promote inclusive transformation.\r\n<blockquote>Smart companies will get out of the way and help the inevitable to happen sooner.\r\n\r\nThe Cluetrain Manifesto (1999)</blockquote>\r\nFor sure, these advances alone are not going to address everything that needs to be fixed in the world. If we look closer, they are actually just a small step, but a very exciting one, for a specific reason. It is not just a matter of providing new tools and working to making them as user-friendly as possible, it is a matter of proposing technologies that are able to transform us socially, not only technically. I am not excited for the 1000-dollar guy simply because he is going to save 100 or 200 bucks in purchasing power using a blockchain-based hedging tool that otherwise would not be accessible to him, nor I am too excited for his possibility of becoming the owner of a small share of the next big thing. These things are going to be important, for him and for us. But the major point here is how they can significantly change the mind and the behavior of many people now excluded from economies in general, as soon as they realize they are actually transforming themselves in entrepreneurs and investors by saving a little money they have power with, that these are real possibilities for them even if starting small. The whole ideas of “entrepreneur”, “business” and “investor” can be redefined sooner than most of us expect if this process goes on. With blockchain, we started a journey of as many heroes as we want, even if many of them did not realize they will be part of it yet.\r\n\r\nGabriel Aleixo is a Researcher and Project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>','Blockchain - a journey of infinite heroes','','inherit','closed','closed','','571-revision-v1','','','2016-03-22 13:50:44','2016-03-22 13:50:44','',571,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/571-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(574,8,'2016-03-22 13:55:33','2016-03-22 13:55:33','','tumblr_nvcofc34sc1ugh5sto2_r1_12801_wcvfnr','','inherit','open','closed','','tumblr_nvcofc34sc1ugh5sto2_r1_12801_wcvfnr','','','2016-03-22 13:55:33','2016-03-22 13:55:33','',571,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/tumblr_nvcofc34sc1ugh5sto2_r1_12801_wcvfnr.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(575,8,'2016-03-22 14:20:37','2016-03-22 14:20:37','<em><strong>As opposed to other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars, which were predicted and anticipated long before, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible  numbers, made possible by rearranging information and technologies we had for years. This, says Gabriel Aleixo, a researcher and project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>, is where the real disruptive potential lies. </strong></em>\r\n\r\nWhenever some kind of revolution starts, there are always the ones who acknowledge its transformations at the very beginning and those who keep believing it is a fad or just a newer instance of something we already had for so long. Right now, there is no better example of that than the emergence of blockchain as a multi-purpose technology, and the myriad of projects that followed its successful creation/deployment in Bitcoin. In the case of the cryptocurrency, even with some significant coverage from the mainstream press many, dismiss it as a mere payment processing tool, no better than the ones offered by hundreds of small startups all over the world. Honestly, this is not necessarily wrong in any way, as some of the enthusiasts like me might think.\r\n\r\nOf course, we will have companies and institutions deliberately attempting to fight it, as these technologies could represent such a progress for society in general that many of their professionals - especially in the intermediation businesses - could not be needed anymore in a few years. But my point is that blockchain technologies have the power to directly lead to a paradigm shift so profound that many could not even relate to this process, inasmuch as that they did not consider something like it before. This is why even among the optimistic crowd some can not go further than limited analogies to existing technologies they think to be utterly innovative.\r\n\r\nIn this regard, it is important to keep in mind, that if we deconstruct Blockchain technology, we really won\'t find entirely new concepts. Public-key cryptography  and distributed networks, for example, have been out there for years. The novelty in blockchain technology, however, consists in its unique capability of generating and communicating consensus about a common database which is maintained and updated through a decentralized network. This in it self was built by rearranging how technologies (we did know very well before) interact in a single technical protocol, so that they could finally solve the problem of random peers agreeing with each other without relying on centralized trust. As Ludwig Wittgenstein wrote in his Philosophical Investigations:\r\n<blockquote>The problems are solved, not by giving new information, but by arranging what we have known since long.\r\nLudwig Wittgenstein (1953).</blockquote>\r\nThe Blockchain concept arose as part of a protocol to secure the creation and the transference of cryptographic tokens, intended to be used as electronic cash, something many brilliant minds in Computer Science considered to be impossible for decades. Differently from other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars which were predicted long before and affected our perspectives of the future, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible numbers, made possible by rearranging information we had for years. Of course there is a huge infrastructure behind it, which costs a lot in terms of energy and equipment, but in the bottom line the technology itself has more to do with the knowledge it embodies and freely spreads as open source code.\r\n\r\nIn this sense, F. A. Hayek points out very clearly in his seminal work The Constitution of Liberty:\r\n<blockquote>The growth of knowledge is of such special importance because, while the material resources will always remain scarce and will have to be reserved for limited purposes, the uses of new knowledge (where we do not make them artificially scarce by patents of monopoly) are unrestricted. Knowledge, once achieved, becomes gratuitously available for the benefit of all. It is through this free gift of the knowledge acquired by the experiments of some members of society that general progress is made possible, that the achievements of those who have gone before facilitate the advance of those who follow.\r\nF.A. Hayek (1960).</blockquote>\r\nThis is why we have this very unique situation. Even if new blockchain-based protocols like Bitcoin or Backfeed lack this materiality (at least for now), the way they can be freely adapted, replicated or deployed is very peculiar, being essentially knowledge gratuitously available for experimentation. We still have to cross the learning curve of programming and even using some of these tools, but at least it seems possible to mantain large and secure distributed networks as public resources, especially when combined with the market incentives built in Bitcoin or Ethereum. How to grow and sustain a decentralized governance is an issue, but as Bill Gates noted blockchain-based technologies are exciting because they are “cheap”. They provide opportunities for real innovation in the foreseeable future in areas dominated by a few players today.\r\n\r\nTake financial services and entrepreneurship as an example. Naturally, things are not going to entirely change in a year or two. But the fact is that, technically speaking, we now have the tools to transform an “exclusive game” in a more inclusive one. These changes are working in a way to include more people through decentralization. In the past, if you had 1000 dollars in your bank account you were very limited in how to protect your savings from inflation or in how to invest them in a new business. If you had 100000 dollars, things definitely got better in terms of accessing better financial tools or being part of an interesting investment fund, but you were still very limited in your possibilities compared to someone who held 10 million dollars. From now on, with blockchain, we can significantly decentralize such services and made them equally available for a much wider range of people. Small savings from people all over the world put together can easily be part of funding a sucessful startup, rather than a few institutional investors, as crowdfunding and equity distribution start to become a thing in blockchain-based platforms.  And no matter if we are talking about 1 dollar or 1 million dollars, hedging tools are also another trend emerging in the cryptoassets and smart contracts arena to decentralize and promote inclusive transformation.\r\n<blockquote>Smart companies will get out of the way and help the inevitable to happen sooner.\r\n\r\nThe Cluetrain Manifesto (1999)</blockquote>\r\nFor sure, these advances alone are not going to address everything that needs to be fixed in the world. If we look closer, they are actually just a small step, but a very exciting one, for a specific reason. It is not just a matter of providing new tools and working to making them as user-friendly as possible, it is a matter of proposing technologies that are able to transform us socially, not only technically. I am not excited for the 1000-dollar guy simply because he is going to save 100 or 200 bucks in purchasing power using a blockchain-based hedging tool that otherwise would not be accessible to him, nor I am too excited for his possibility of becoming the owner of a small share of the next big thing. These things are going to be important, for him and for us. But the major point here is how they can significantly change the mind and the behavior of many people, currently excluded from economies in general, as soon as they realize that they are actually transforming themselves in entrepreneurs and investors by saving a little money. Concepts like “entrepreneur”, “business” and “investor” can be redefined sooner than most of us expect if this process goes on. With blockchain, we started a journey of as many heroes as we want, even if many of them did not realize they will be part of it yet.\r\n\r\nGabriel Aleixo is a Researcher and Project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>','Blockchain - a journey of infinite heroes','','inherit','closed','closed','','571-revision-v1','','','2016-03-22 14:20:37','2016-03-22 14:20:37','',571,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/571-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(576,1,'2016-03-22 17:09:54','2016-03-22 17:09:54',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','576','','','2016-04-19 10:43:52','2016-04-19 10:43:52','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=576',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(577,1,'2016-03-22 17:09:54','2016-03-22 17:09:54',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','577','','','2016-04-19 10:43:52','2016-04-19 10:43:52','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=577',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(578,1,'2016-03-22 17:09:54','2016-03-22 17:09:54','','Team','','publish','closed','closed','','team-2','','','2016-04-19 10:43:52','2016-04-19 10:43:52','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=578',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(579,1,'2016-03-22 17:09:54','2016-03-22 17:09:54','','Backfeed Website','','publish','closed','closed','','backfeed-website-2','','','2016-04-19 10:43:52','2016-04-19 10:43:52','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=579',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(580,1,'2016-03-28 07:11:13','2016-03-28 07:11:13','<em><strong>As opposed to other disruptive technologies like drones, 3D printers or self-driving cars, which were predicted and anticipated long before, blockchain lacks this visual appeal. It is a mix of code, processing power and (for most) intangible  numbers, made possible by rearranging information and technologies we had for years. This, says Gabriel Aleixo, a researcher and project Coordinator at <a href=\"http://itsrio.org/en/\">ITS Rio</a>, is where the real disruptive potential lies. </strong></em>\n\nWhenever some kind of revolution starts, there are always the ones who acknowledge its transformations at the very beginning and those who keep believing it is a fad or just a newer instance of something we already had for so long. Right now, there is no better example of t